19.   what is inheritance anc explain the multilevel inheritance.

        Inheritance is an OOP concept where one class acquires properties and behaviors from another class

        it helps:
            reuse
            extensible
            maintaining hierarchical relationships
        Inheritance is used to extending/reuse functionality of one class to another class.

        multilevel ->> Grandparent ->> parent ->> child

        example:
            class GrandParent:
                def grandparent(self):
                    print("Grand Parent class")
            class Parent(GrandParent):
                def parent(self):
                    print("Parent class")
            class Child(Parent):
                def child(self):
                    print("child class")

            ch = Child()
            ch.child()
            ch.parent()
            ch.grandparent()
        🔹 Real-World Analogy

            Think of a company hierarchy:

            Employee → basic info

            Manager (inherits Employee) → manages team

            Senior Manager (inherits Manager) → handles multiple teams

            👉 Senior Manager automatically gets:

                Employee features

                Manager features

                Plus its own

            🔹 Key Benefits

                Promotes reusability

                Supports hierarchical design

                Makes system scalable and maintainable

            🔹 When to Use Multilevel Inheritance

                Use it when:

                    There is a clear “is-a” relationship

                    Each level adds meaningful specialization

                    You are modeling real-world hierarchy

            🔹 Caution (Important for Interviews)

                    Too many levels → tight coupling

                    Harder debugging and testing

                    Prefer composition over inheritance in complex systems
