Understanding Class, Static, and Instance in Python OOP

In Python OOP, there are 3 important things:

    Instance Variables & Instance Methods
    Class Variables & Class Methods
    Static Methods

    Most beginners get confused because all three look similar, but they solve different real-world problems.

1. Instance Variables & Instance Methods

    An instance variable belongs to an object (individual instance).
    Each object gets its own separate copy of the data.
    An instance method works with object-specific data using self.

Real-World Example — Bank Account

    Every bank customer has:

        different account number
        different balance
        different name
    These should NOT be shared.

Why Use Instance Variables?

    Because every object has different data.

When to Use?

    Use instance variables when data changes per object.

    Examples:

        Real-world System	                        Instance Variables
        Student	                                    name, marks
        Car	                                        speed, fuel
        Employee	                                salary
        Food Delivery	                            order status
        E-commerce	                                cart items

Where Used in Real Projects?

    Very heavily used in:

        Backend APIs
        FastAPI
        Django Models
        Banking systems
        Microservices
        Game development

---------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Class Variables & Class Methods

    A class variable belongs to the class itself.

    It is SHARED among all objects.

    A class method uses cls and works with shared class-level data.

    Real-World Example — Company Employees

        All employees share:

            company name
            leave policy
            HR rules

    These should not be duplicated for every employee.

Example:
    class Employee:

        company_name = "Google"   # class variable

        def __init__(self, name):
            self.name = name

        @classmethod
        def change_company(cls, new_name):
            cls.company_name = new_name


        emp1 = Employee("Venkat")
        emp2 = Employee("Ravi")

        print(emp1.company_name)
        print(emp2.company_name)

        Employee.change_company("Microsoft")

        print(emp1.company_name)
        print(emp2.company_name)

Why Use Class Variables?

    To store COMMON shared data.

When to Use?

    Use when all objects should share same value.

    | System      | Class Variable |
    | ----------- | -------------- |
    | School      | school_name    |
    | Company     | company_policy |
    | Game        | max_players    |
    | API Service | API_VERSION    |
    | E-commerce  | tax_percentage |

Where Used in Real Projects?

    Very common in:

        Configuration systems
        FastAPI settings
        Database connection pools
        Constants
        Shared cache
        Counters


    class APIRequest:

        total_requests = 0

        def __init__(self):
            APIRequest.total_requests += 1


    r1 = APIRequest()
    r2 = APIRequest()
    r3 = APIRequest()

    print(APIRequest.total_requests)

    All objects share same counter.

    Class variable lives only once in memory.
    All objects reference same value.

3. Static Methods


    A static method:

        belongs logically to class

        but does NOT use:
            self
            cls
    It is just a utility/helper function placed inside class.

Why Use Static Methods?

    To group utility logic related to class.

When to Use?

    Use when method:

        does not access object data
        does not access class data
        is logically related to class
Examples:
            | System         | Static Method       |
            | -------------- | ------------------- |
            | Authentication | password hashing    |
            | Payment        | currency conversion |
            | File System    | file validation     |
            | Ecommerce      | discount calculator |
            | Banking        | interest formula    |

Real-World Analogy — Food Delivery App

    Imagine Swiggy or Zomato.

    Instance Variables

        Each order has:
            order_id
            customer_name
            delivery_address
        Different per order.

    Class Variables

        Shared globally:
            platform_fee = 10
        Same for all orders.

    Static Methods

        Utility functions:
            calculate_distance()
            validate_phone_number()

        No order-specific state needed.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Why not use normal functions instead of static methods?

    Good question.

    You CAN.

    But static methods improve:

        code organization
        readability
        logical grouping
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Can Class Method Access Instance Variable?

NO directly.

Because class method has no object (self).











